<br>
I took over as GL of ICoN last December, when our guild was all but dead. There are a LOT of former ICoNers in other guilds now, many left due to poor management and lack of high level challenges in the past two and half years. I don't fault any of the people who left during those trying times - I almost left too before I decided to stick it out and try to rebuild the guild. When I took over the guild last December, several former ICoNers decided to return and help me remake the guild - or so I thought at the time. The next month I learned a very hard lesson about the underhanded motivations of some people. A former GL of ICoN who I brought back as an officer began arranging an under the table deal with some dishonest people in Eternal Haven. Basically, if this guy could talk ICoN into merging with Eternal Haven and bring over lots of people, he would be granted an officer position with Eternal Haven. Needless to say, we found out about the deception and the merge talks with Eternal Haven quickly broke down. That person left ICoN and took several of his friends to Eternal Haven. Barely a month later, Eternal Haven suffered a major civil war which almost tore that guild apart. The deceivers from ICoN had joined with the deceivers in Eternal Haven who then moved on to form a new guild, Endless Prophecy. The people in Eternal Haven today are good people and I consider them friends. They were the victims just as ICoN was a victim. That group of deceivers then moved on and joined Chaotic Delusions, where barely two months later, that guild blew apart. That group of a dozen or so people have now moved on to one of the "uber" guilds. In their wake is a long line of destroyed guilds, broken guilds, and hurt people. I can't believe that those people take pleasure in destruction. I think their motivation was simply to trade the dreams of others to jockey for more power and more prominence with larger and larger guilds. However, the selfcenteredness of those dozen or so people have hurt scores of other people, people they don't seem to care about. As long as they got what they considered to be "uber status" they really didn't care what they left behind. It is similar to the business takeover frenzy in the 1980's where entire companies were bought and dismantled because the pieces brought higher profit to the shareholders, meanwhile workers and families were left behind in poverty. It is the same kind of greed we have seen with Enron and Worldcom and other companies. I realize EQ is "just a game" but the behavior of some within the game is similar to what has happened with the Enrons of the real world. It all boils down to greed. Simple and selfish greed.<br>
<br>
When a guild member sticks around long enough to get their epic or some other uber item and then they leave, using that newly acquired epic to gain entry into a more uber guild, it is simply greed. When a guild member uses guilds and people to "move up" they are in fact showing just what low lifes they truly are. If they are so eager to step on others in game to rise higher, then they will do the same thing to people in the real world. It is a major character flaw that manifests itself in game because the flaw also exists in their real lives. It is truly a shame that most guilds won't investigate new players very closely. Does that new player have their epic? Is the guild in great need for a particular class? Then the guild tends to turn a blind eye to the player's past. Two months ago I removed ICoN's only high level monk because he refused to turn off anon status, thus hiding the guild tag and impeding his taking part in guild chat, not to mention the fact that he was breaking our posted rules to remain anon. We lost our only high level puller and we are still in desperate need of high level monks today. But would I accept just any high level monk, regardless of their history, because the guild needs a decent puller? To be honest, not too long ago I probably would have ignored their history and taken them into the guild, because we "need" good pullers. But the comments of those of you in this thread have once again reminded me that a single quality player is worth far more than a dozen poor quality players. Thank you for reminding me of that.<br>
